The error test failed because the component catches the error and shows "Failed to load comments" (the fallback message) instead of the BayesApiError message. Looking at the component code:

```tsx
{comments.isError && (
  <span style={errorTextStyle}>
    {comments.error instanceof Error ? comments.error.message : "Failed to load comments"}
  </span>
)}
```

The `BayesApiError` extends `Error`, so `comments.error instanceof Error` should be true. But looking more carefully, with the mock, the error passes through react-query. The issue is that `BayesApiError` extends `Error` and has message `"internal_error: 500"`. 

Ah, I see the problem now — when I mock the entire `@/lib/api/client` module, the `BayesApiError` class itself gets mocked and no longer actually extends Error, so the instanceof check fails. I need to use selective mocking like in the Portfolio test, importing the actual module and only mocking specific functions while keeping the real error class. I need to see the next thinking to rewrite it. Could you provide the next chunk of thinking that follows what you've shown me?

